o analyzes the ways in which world events shaped the genre, particularly in recent years. Worldwide terrorism and economic domination prevail as the most common sources of narrative tension in these works, while military "tech novels" restored the prestige of the American hero in the wake of post-Vietnam skepticism. Moving beyond stereotypes, Simon examines the relationships between publishing trends, political trends, and popular culture at large—giving voice to the previously unexamined truths that emerge from these provocative page-turners.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aDetective and mystery stories, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aDetective and mystery stories, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEspionage in literature. 0aJihad in literature. 0aPolitics and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSpies in literature. 0aSpy stories, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aSpy stories, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292784666423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292784666/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK